By ‘ saltus ’ are meant pasture landa in the forests on the hills (Cic. Orat. pro Quintio, c. 6, Long’s note). That Quin- tilian had many of these may be an exagge- ration. Pliny the younger was Quintilian’s pupil, and so were many of the leading men in politics and literature. He also taught the two grand-nephews of Domitian (Inst. 1. iv. prooem.)‚ who invested him with the titleof consul, though he never bore the office. Ventidius Bassus was a. native of Picenum, and in the Soeial War, according to one story, being at the time a. child in arms, he was carried captive with his mother to Rome, and appeared in the triumphal procession of Cn. Pompeius Stra- bo, 13.c. 89. When he grew up he gained his livelihood by letting out mules and carriages. He became acquainted with C.
